#### W-3: Working with Human Resources
*Strategy:* Draft + Assert
*See also:* W-2: Understanding Your Rights If You're Let Go, Li-1: Preparing for a Difficult Conversation
*My Man Jeeves:* _It may be useful to note that Human Resources exists to protect the company. This is not a matter of cynicism — it is the department's actual mandate. An HR representative who assists an employee does so because assisting the employee also serves the company's interest, which is, one acknowledges, frequently the case. An understanding of this alignment — the occasions upon which one's interests and the company's overlap, and those upon which they diverge — represents the difference between employing HR effectively and finding oneself somewhat surprised by the outcome._
*The spec:*
::: prompt
I need to deal with an HR situation at work.
My situation: [performance review / workplace conflict /
harassment or discrimination / requesting accommodation /
documenting something / asking about benefits or policy]
What happened: [describe factually — dates, people, what was
said or done]
What I want to happen: [specific outcome]
Please help me:
1. Understand how HR is likely to view this situation
2. Draft what I should say or write — factual, professional, documented
3. Tell me what to put in writing vs. what to say in person
4. Flag anything I should be careful about
:::
*What to do with the output:* Put everything in writing. Email yourself a summary after every meeting. Use the phrase "per our conversation on [date]" in follow-up emails. This is not paranoia — it is the documentation standard that HR itself uses. Match their rigor.

::: tip
_"I need to write my annual self-review. Here are my accomplishments this year: [list]. Write a first draft in first person that is specific, uses metrics where possible, and frames my work in terms of business impact."_
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The performance review is one of the most anxiety-producing rituals in modern work life. Murphy (2020, "Performance Evaluation Will Not Die, But It Should") argues that traditional reviews are poor predictors of actual performance and better predictors of reviewer bias. Knowing this doesn't eliminate the anxiety but it contextualizes it — the game is impression management, not objective assessment. Your Agent can help you play the game without pretending it isn't one. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): Workplace conflict is the most common source of daily stress in American adults (APA Stress in America survey, annual — verify latest year). The vast majority goes unreported because reporting requires trusting a system (HR) that employees correctly perceive as aligned with management. The entry should be honest about this dynamic while still being practically useful: there are times when going to HR serves you, and there are times when documenting independently is the better move. Your Agent can help you assess which is which. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: Documentation best practices for workplace harassment and discrimination. EEOC guidelines exist but are written for lawyers. The entry should translate: what to save, how to save it (personal device, personal email, not company systems), the difference between an informal complaint and a formal report, timeline requirements, and the retaliation protections under Title VII (and their practical limits). -->

