#### W-7: Using Your Agent to Get More Done
*Strategy:* Navigate + Draft (Expert Role)
*See also:* W-3: Working with HR (for the performance review spec), W-1: Getting a New Job (for job-search automation)
*My Man Jeeves:* _It would appear that the billionaire class did not achieve their productivity by working harder. They achieved it by engaging persons to attend to those portions of work that are repetitive, formulaic, or requiring of research for which they themselves lacked the time. Email drafts. Report summaries. Data formatting. Meeting preparation. Status updates. Proposal boilerplate. The work, as it were, behind the work. The reader now has access to the same staff — one simply refers to it as "being more productive" on the performance review._
*The spec:*
::: prompt
I want to use my AI Agent to work more efficiently.
My role: [job title or brief description]
The tasks that take up most of my time:
[list the repetitive, time-consuming, or formulaic parts of your job]
The tools I use: [email, spreadsheets, specific software]
Please help me:
1. Identify which of my tasks an Agent can handle or accelerate
2. Give me the specific specs I would use for each one
3. Tell me which tasks I should NOT hand off
   (judgment calls, relationship work, things that need my voice)
4. Show me how to review Agent output quickly so the quality
   stays high and the voice stays mine
:::
*What to do with the output:* Start with one task. The one you dread most or the one that eats the most time. Run it through your Agent for a week. Measure the difference. Then add another. The compound effect is the point — you are not replacing yourself, you are multiplying your output. Your employer measures output, not hours. That is capitalism working for you for once.

::: tip
The performance review spec: _"Summarize my accomplishments this quarter based on these notes: [paste notes]. Write it in first person, active voice, with specific metrics where possible. Make it sound like a high performer wrote it — because one did."_
:::


::: meme
Every automation tool in history — the loom, the spreadsheet, the assembly line — was sold to management as productivity and feared by workers as replacement. The workers who learned the loom first kept their jobs. The ones who learned spreadsheets first got promoted. Your Agent is the current version of this pattern. The playbook has not changed in 200 years. Learn it first.
:::


::: also
To make this Expert Role persistent across sessions, save it as a *Project* (Claude), *Gem* (Gemini), or *Custom GPT* (ChatGPT). See [Appendix G](06-appendix-g-feature-table.xhtml).
:::


*Common work automation Expert Role specs:*
::: prompt
Act as my executive assistant. I need to send an email to [person]
about [topic]. The tone should be [professional / friendly / firm].
Here are my key points: [list]. Draft the email.
:::
::: prompt
Act as a business analyst. I have this data: [paste or describe].
Summarize the key trends, flag anything unusual, and draft
three bullet points I can use in my weekly status update.
:::
::: prompt
Act as a meeting preparation assistant. I have a meeting about
[topic] with [audience]. Here is the background: [paste or describe].
Give me: the three questions they are most likely to ask,
a one-page summary of the key points, and a suggested agenda.
:::
::: prompt
Act as a proposal writer. I need to respond to this RFP / client
request: [paste or describe]. My company's strengths are [list].
Draft the response. I will edit for accuracy and voice.
:::

